VALUES
(44, 26, 8, 1, 18, 14, 14, NULL, 'Divine Power Over Life', 'Both passages emphasize God''s ability to perform what seems impossible, such as raising the dead or granting life to Sarah. This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention in human circumstances.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 8, 43, 5, 28, 29, 'that God should raise the dead', 'Resurrection of the Dead', 'This connection highlights the theme of resurrection in both passages. Acts 26:8 questions the incredibility of God raising the dead, while John 5:28-29 describes the resurrection of those in graves.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 9, 54, 1, 13, 13, 'contrary to the name of Jesus', 'Ignorance and Unbelief Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of acting contrary to Jesus due to ignorance. Acts 26:9 mentions doing things contrary to Jesus, while 1 Timothy 1:13 highlights acting ignorantly in unbelief.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 9, 44, 22, 8, 8, 'Jesus of Nazareth', 'Connection of Jesus of Nazareth', 'Both passages emphasize the name ''Jesus of Nazareth.'' In Acts 26:9, the speaker acknowledges actions against this name, while in Acts 22:8, Jesus identifies himself with the same name, highlighting the significance of this identity in the context of persecution.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 9, 48, 1, 13, 14, 'contrary to the name of Jesus', 'Persecution of the Church', 'Both passages emphasize the speaker''s past actions against the followers of Jesus. Acts 26:9 reflects a personal conviction to oppose Jesus, while Galatians 1:13-14 details the extent of persecution within the Jewish faith.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 9, 50, 3, 6, 6, 'contrary to the name of Jesus', 'Persecution of the Church', 'This connection highlights the theme of zeal in both passages, where Acts 26:9 reflects a personal conviction to act against Jesus, while Philippians 3:6 describes zeal in persecuting the church. Both emphasize a commitment to actions contrary to the early Christian faith.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 9, 43, 15, 21, 21, 'contrary to the name of Jesus', 'Opposition to Jesus'' Name', 'This connection highlights the theme of opposition to Jesus and his followers. In Acts, the speaker reflects on actions taken against Jesus'' name, while John notes that such actions occur because of ignorance of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 9, 43, 16, 2, 3, 'contrary to the name of Jesus', 'Persecution for Belief in Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by believers in Jesus. Both passages emphasize that individuals may act against followers of Christ, believing they are serving God, as seen in Paul''s reflection on his past actions and Jesus'' warning about future persecution.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 9, 44, 3, 6, 6, 'Jesus of Nazareth', 'Contrasting Actions in Jesus'' Name', 'This connection highlights the contrast between Paul''s initial opposition to Jesus and Peter''s proclamation of healing in His name. Both passages emphasize the significance of ''Jesus of Nazareth'' in their respective contexts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 10, 44, 8, 3, 3, 'shut up in prison', 'Saul''s Persecution of the Church', 'Both passages emphasize Saul''s actions against the church, detailing his imprisonment of believers. Acts 26:10 reflects on his authority and involvement in their deaths, while Acts 8:3 describes his aggressive pursuit of Christians.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 10, 44, 9, 13, 14, 'many of the saints did I shut up in prison', 'Connection of Saul''s Persecution', 'Both passages emphasize Saul''s actions against the saints in Jerusalem. Acts 26:10 recounts his imprisonment and approval of their deaths, while Acts 9:13-14 highlights his authority to bind those who call on Jesus'' name.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 10, 46, 15, 9, 9, NULL, 'Paul''s Persecution of the Church', 'This connection highlights Paul''s acknowledgment of his past actions against the church. Both passages emphasize his role in persecuting the saints and his feelings of unworthiness as an apostle.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 10, 19, 16, 3, 3, 'saints', 'Connection of Saints in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''saints'' in both passages. Acts 26:10 refers to the persecution of ''saints,'' while Psalms 16:3 expresses delight in ''the saints that are in the earth.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 10, 45, 15, 25, 26, 'saints', 'Connection of Saints in Jerusalem', 'This connection highlights the focus on ''saints'' in both passages. In Acts, the mention of imprisoning ''saints'' contrasts with Romans, where Paul goes to ''minister unto the saints'' in Jerusalem, indicating a shift from persecution to support.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 10, 48, 1, 13, 13, NULL, 'Persecution of the Church', 'Both passages emphasize the intense persecution of the church by Paul. Acts 26:10 describes his actions in imprisoning saints, while Galatians 1:13 highlights his efforts in persecuting the church of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 10, 49, 1, 1, 1, 'many of the saints', 'Connection of Saints in Paul’s Writings', 'This connection highlights the term ''saints'' as it appears in both passages. In Acts, Paul refers to ''the saints'' he persecuted, while in Ephesians, he addresses ''the saints'' in Ephesus, indicating a continuity in his ministry towards believers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 11, 40, 10, 17, 17, NULL, 'Persecution in Synagogues', 'Both passages emphasize the persecution faced by believers in synagogues. Acts 26:11 describes the punishment and compulsion to blaspheme, while Matthew 10:17 warns of being delivered to councils and scourged in synagogues.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 11, 44, 13, 45, 45, 'compelled them to blaspheme', 'Persecution and Blasphemy Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of blasphemy and persecution present in both passages. In Acts 26:11, the speaker mentions compelling others to blaspheme, while in Acts 13:45, the Jews are described as contradicting and blaspheming against Paul.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 11, 44, 22, 19, 19, 'in every synagogue', 'Persecution of Believers', 'Both passages emphasize the persecution of believers in synagogues. Acts 26:11 mentions punishing them in every synagogue, while Acts 22:19 refers to imprisoning and beating them in the same context.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 11, 21, 9, 3, 3, 'mad against them', 'Madness and Evil in Humanity', 'This connection highlights the theme of madness and evil present in human hearts. Both passages emphasize the destructive nature of such madness, with Acts 26:11 illustrating personal persecution driven by madness, while Ecclesiastes 9:3 reflects on the inherent evil and madness in humanity.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 11, 41, 3, 28, 28, 'compelled them to blaspheme', 'Connection of Blasphemy Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of blasphemy present in both passages. In Acts, the act of compelling others to blaspheme is mentioned, while in Mark, the forgiveness of blasphemies is emphasized.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 11, 41, 13, 9, 9, NULL, 'Persecution in Synagogues', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of persecution in synagogues. Acts 26:11 describes the punishment and compulsion to blaspheme, while Mark 13:9 warns of being beaten in synagogues.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 11, 42, 6, 11, 11, 'exceedingly mad', 'Madness and Persecution Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of madness in relation to persecution. In Acts, the speaker describes being ''exceedingly mad'' in his actions against believers, while in Luke, the individuals are ''filled with madness'' as they plot against Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 12, 44, 9, 1, 8, 'authority and commission from the chief priests', 'Saul''s Journey to Damascus', 'Both passages emphasize Saul''s journey to Damascus, where he sought authority to persecute Christians. Acts 26:12 references his commission from the chief priests, while Acts 9:1-8 details his actions and the divine encounter he experienced there.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 12, 44, 22, 5, 11, 'authority and commission from the chief priests', 'Paul''s Journey to Damascus', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s journey to Damascus, where he received authority from the chief priests to persecute Christians. Acts 26:12 references this commission, while Acts 22:5-11 details the events that transpired during that journey, including his encounter with Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 12, 11, 21, 8, 10, 'authority and commission from the chief priests', 'Authority and False Accusation', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority being misused to execute injustice. In both passages, individuals act under the guise of authority—Paul with the chief priests and Jezebel with Ahab''s seal—to carry out wrongful actions against the innocent.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 12, 19, 94, 20, 21, 'authority and commission from the chief priests', 'Authority and Injustice', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority being used to perpetrate injustice. In Acts, the authority from the chief priests leads to persecution, while Psalms speaks of those who gather against the righteous and condemn the innocent.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 12, 23, 10, 1, 1, 'authority and commission from the chief priests', 'Authority and Unrighteous Decrees', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in both passages. Acts 26:12 refers to authority from the chief priests, while Isaiah 10:1 warns against those who decree unrighteousness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 12, 24, 26, 8, 8, 'authority and commission from the chief priests', 'Authority and Opposition', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority leading to opposition. In Acts, Paul mentions his ''authority and commission'' from the chief priests, paralleling Jeremiah''s experience of being confronted by priests and prophets who opposed him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 26, 12, 24, 29, 26, 27, 'authority and commission from the chief priests', 'Authority and Prophetic Reproof', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in both passages. In Acts, Paul mentions his authority from the chief priests, while Jeremiah discusses the authority of priests to reprove false prophets.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
